    <h3>A "bit" is a single binary digit, a one or a zero.  There are two different places in computing where bits get counted. In color displays, and in processing.</h3>
    <h3>The number of bits tells you how many colors can simultaneously be displayed on the screen.  For example, "8-bit color" means that you can only have a maximum of 256 colors on your display.  Modern systems use "24-bit color", 8 bits each for red, blue, and green intensities, for a total of 16.78 million colors.</h3>
